	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Cost and benefits of non-tariff measures in the Kenyan cut-flower sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>An OECD report has been posted on the costs and benefits of non-tariff measures, including a case study of the Kenyan cut-flower sector. The report notes that Kenya is among the top ten sources of cut-flower imports into OECD countries, especially the EU. It notes the growing importance of non-tariff barriers within the expanding global trade in cut flowers, most notably SPS controls, but also production and labour standards. The paper focuses on the impact of SPS standards in the light of exporter concerns over the trade effects of such measures.</p><p>Using modelling techniques the analysis looks at four different scenarios:</p>
<ul>

<li>a ‘status quo’ scenario based on current low rates of inspection;</li>

<li>an enhanced inspection scenario, but with no production adjustments taking place in Kenya;</li>

<li>a scenario of ‘enhanced inspection with delays’;</li>

<li>production adjustments in response to enhanced inspections, with delays caused to final delivery.</li>

</ul>
<p>The analysis argues that ‘the results of the simulations suggest that the increase of inspection costs for the EU outweigh the benefits of reduced infestation for the EU producers’ and that tighter inspections lead to losses for foreign suppliers, since this can delay final delivery and lead to a loss of quality, and consequently revenues. However, ‘improving production methods in exchange for reduced inspection tightness would also lead to diminished profits for foreign suppliers because of higher production costs.’</p><p>The report notes that the ‘costs related to inspection programmes may become an entry barrier for certain foreign producers.’ This raises ‘concerns regarding market participation, particularly, in low-income countries.’ The report further notes that ‘often this unequal ability to meet standards causes dualism in the industry affected by the new regulatory environment’ (i.e. one section of the industry serves the domestic market while another section serves the export market). Overall the report concludes that ‘cost-efficient improvements of production methods in countries exporting to the EU that can result in lower contamination rates, therefore can be seen as a major step to avoid costs on both sides of the border.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>OECD, ‘Case studies of the costs and benefits of non-tariff measures: cheese, shrimp and flowers’, TAD/TC/CA/WP(2009)2/FINAL, 30 June 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.oecd.org/officialdocuments/displaydocumentpdf/?cote=tad/tc/ca/wp(2009)2/final&amp;doclanguage=en" target="_self">http://www.oecd.org/officialdocuments/displaydocumentpdf/?cote=tad/tc/ca...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The most significant finding of the OECD analysis is that SPS inspections can act as a particular barrier to market entry for low-income countries. Against this background, if least developed countries are to be assisted in diversifying their export base, consideration needs to be given to a programme of measures that can help LDC suppliers to both gain and maintain a position in profitably supplying the EU market, despite the high SPS-related market entry costs. A number of possible measures to assist LDC suppliers are potentially available. The first involves ‘aid for trade’ support in partially defraying the costs of intense inspection which new LDC suppliers face when building up a track record for the establishment of a ‘risk-based’ inspection schedule. Once risk-based inspections take place, this tends to reduce both the frequency and intensity of inspections, thereby reducing the overall costs of inspection. The second possible measure relates to the integration of certain aspects of SPS controls into private-sector inspection programmes (e.g. GLOBALGAP) and recognition of the efficacy of these inspections via reduced levels of inspection by public-sector officials at the point of entry. This could build on two existing initiatives: the localisation of standards application, through the KENYAGAP translation of GLOBALGAP standards into local standards that are consistent with local production-system realities (without compromising the underlying EU standards); and the establishment of initiatives such as the recently launched Assured Trader Scheme (ATS) in the UK, which, by recognising the equivalence of certain private-sector control measures, requires lower levels of inspection of consignments imported by reputable traders who already meet the required high standards (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/admin/content/edit/7614/#_Call_for_early" target="_self">Call for early action to ease controls on DR banana exports</a>’).</p><p>Overall this would appear to strengthen the case for the establishment of a clear and coherent development dimension to EU SPS- and food-safety policy if stricter EU SPS- and food-safety controls are not to marginalise LDC producers from international trade in a range of important agricultural sub-sectors.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

